    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>First, Pay the Debt</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gil Ehrenkranz letter responds to Bob Herbert's July 24 Op-Ed column, which opposed Republicans' proposals for income-tax cut; advocates using federal budget surplus to pay down national debt</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert criticizes Republicans who advocate irresponsibly large income tax cuts (column, July 24). His counterproposal is that the portion of the budget surplus not already committed to spending, not needed to shore up Social Security and not derived from the Medicare trust fund be spent on new federal programs. But he doesn't mention an even more responsible alternative: using the money to pay down the national debt.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert criticizes Republicans who advocate irresponsibly large income tax cuts (column, July 24). His counterproposal is that the portion of the budget surplus not already committed to spending, not needed to shore up Social Security and not derived from the Medicare trust fund be spent on new federal programs. But he doesn't mention an even more responsible alternative: using the money to pay down the national debt.</p>
        <p>The annual savings on interest charges could pay for new programs. To spend the surplus without paying down the debt sentences us to financing permanent government programs while continuing to shoulder the interest burden in perpetuity.</p>
        <p>GIL EHRENKRANZ  Rockville, Md., July 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
